    "summary": "The Potsdam Conference, held July 17 – August 2, 1945, in the Berlin suburb of Potsdam, was the final wartime summit of the major Allied powers and the last meeting of the Big Three — Harry Truman (who had succeeded Roosevelt in April), Winston Churchill (replaced partway through by Clement Attlee following the British general election), and Joseph Stalin. The conference occurred after Germany's defeat but before Japan's surrender and addressed the administration of occupied Germany, reparations, territorial questions in Europe, and the war against Japan.\n\nThe Potsdam Declaration, issued to Japan on July 26, demanded unconditional surrender or face prompt and utter destruction. On July 16, the day the conference opened, the United States had successfully tested its first nuclear weapon at Trinity in New Mexico. Truman informed Stalin of a powerful new weapon, though Stalin already had intelligence on the Manhattan Project through Soviet espionage. Japan's rejection of the Potsdam Declaration's terms led to the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki.\n\nPotsdam produced agreements on the treatment of occupied Germany, including the four-power division into American, British, French, and Soviet zones, and the de-Nazification and demilitarization of German society. However, tensions between Western allies and the Soviet Union were already evident, with disputes over reparations, the occupation of Poland, and the political future of Eastern Europe foreshadowing the [[event:113|Cold War]] that would quickly follow.",
